Svelte and Solid both need a reactive accessor when query inputs can change.

```ts
// Svelte
const todos = new QuerySubscription(() =>
  projectId ? app.todos.where({ projectId }) : undefined,
);
```

```ts
// Solid
const [projectId] = createSignal<string | undefined>();
const todos = useAll(() =>
  projectId() ? { query: app.todos.where({ projectId: projectId() }) } : undefined,
);
```

Do not build the query once up front; pass a function so later input changes are tracked.

Use `db.batch(...)` for two optimistic UI writes that should appear locally together as soon as the batch commits.

Use `db.transaction(...)` for two writes that must stay staged until authority accepts them, then become globally visible together.

```ts
const batchResult = db.batch((batch) => {
  batch.update(app.todos, a, { done: true });
  batch.update(app.todos, b, { done: true });
});

const txResult = await db.transaction(async (tx) => {
  tx.update(app.todos, a, { done: true });
  tx.update(app.todos, b, { done: true });
});
await txResult.wait({ tier: "global" });
```
